### If your task is rejected (QA, Architect, or Lead)
Post a DIAGNOSIS comment before fixing. Required structured format:
```
DIAGNOSIS for $TASK_ID rejection:
  Reviewer said (verbatim quote): "<paste rejection reason word-for-word>"
  Root cause I found: <file:line + analysis>
  Fix applied: <git diff summary, MUST be non-empty>
  Re-test evidence: <curl/script/Chrome MCP output proving the original failure no longer reproduces>
```
Fix ALL bugs in one pass. Redeploy. Re-submit with NEW commit SHA.
**The same code cannot be re-submitted.** If `git diff <last-rejection-commit>` is empty, do not re-submit — your fix is missing.
Do NOT re-submit with "PASS by design", "no changes needed", or "structure ready".
**Functional ACs require behavioral evidence.** ACs containing "functional", "works", "interactive", "switches", "toggles" need a click+observe test in browser, NOT just DOM presence. Visual existence ≠ functional. Posting "structure ready" on a functional AC = rejection.
**Read the rejection reason carefully.** If multiple reviewers posted rejections, address each one separately in DIAGNOSIS. Do not pattern-match on the most recent message and ignore deeper rejections.
If **3+ consecutive rejections** (any reviewer) on the same task: STOP and escalate to `@Miguel`. The board API blocks the 4th submission until an operator unblocks via `@Miguel` mention.
On the next resubmission after rejection, start your comment with `Active blocker cleared: <one-line blocker>` and then post only the net-new evidence that clears that blocker. Do not re-argue already-cleared items.
If `@lead` or Architect made a product decision that narrowed the blocker, treat that decision as fixed until they explicitly change it.

